text: Angumycinones A and B, two new angucyclic quinones from Streptomyces sp. KMC004 isolated from acidic mine drainage q Hyun Bong Park a,b, Jae Kyun Lee c, Kang Ro Lee b,(cid:2), Hak Cheol Kwon a,⇑ Article history: Received 15 July 2013 Revised 20 October 2013 Accepted 24 October 2013 Available online 31 October 2013 Keywords: Streptomyces Angucyclinone Angumycinone Acidic mine drainage Microorganisms are a fertile resource for natural product-based drug discovery programs. In particular, terrestrial soil-derived Streptomyces species have been extensively studied because they can potentially provide pharmaceutical candidates; approximately 70% of clinically useful antibiotics are derived from natural sources.1 However, the chemical redundancy of products isolated from these bacteria has become one of the current challenges in the discovery of novel natural product-derived drug candidates.2 One approach to overcome this problem is to utilize Streptomyces species derived from unique habitats, such as marine environ- ments,3 mutualistic associations with hosts,4 etc.; these strains have been exploited to provide novel microbial chemotypes over the last few years. Many recent investigations have uncovered compelling evidence that the Streptomyces species derived from unique environmental samples might lead to the discovery of sec- ondary metabolites with signiﬁcant biological activity.5 Acidic mine drainage is generated by the oxidative reactions that result from the exposure of sulﬁde minerals, such as iron pyrite or iron disulﬁde, to the atmosphere. Kwon). j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / t e t l e t Two new angucyclic quinones, angumycinones A (1) and B (2) and six known angucyclinone analogues (3–8) were isolated from a liquid culture extract of the Streptomyces sp. KMC004 strain from acidic coal mine drainage. The structures of these compounds were established using extensive spectroscopic data analyses, including NMR, HRFABMS, UV, CD, and X-ray crystallography. Compounds 1–8 were tested for antimicrobial activity against ten pathogenic microbial or fungal strains. Angumycinone B (2) exhibited antimicrobial activity against Micrococcus luteus, Enterococcus hirae, and methicillin-resistant Staphylo- coccus aureus (MRSA) with minimum inhibitory concentration values of 0.78, 1.56, and 12.5 lg/mL, respectively. Contents lists available at ScienceDirect Tetrahedron Letters 55 (2014) 63–66 metabolism of diverse microbes.7 Under harsh environmental con- ditions, such as acidic mine drainage, microorganisms may face ecological competition, driving their metabolic potential and requiring the biosynthesis of new secondary metabolites.8

The Streptomyces sp. KMC004 strain was isolated from an acidic mine drainage sample (209 ppm Fe, 6.7 ppm Mn, 0.8 ppm Pb, and 0.8 ppm Cu; pH 3.0) collected from the Young-dong abandoned coal mine located at Gangneung, South Korea, during our ongoing investigation of novel secondary metabolites from microorganisms collected from unique environments. The strain was most likely a Streptomyces sp. based on the 98.3% 16S rRNA sequence similarity with the Streptomyces chryseus strain (EU841613). The Streptomy- ces sp. KMC004 strain was cultivated in YM liquid medium (5 g of yeast and 30 g of malt in 1 L of distilled water) for 10 days at 25 (cid:3)C. The initial high-performance liquid chromatography mass spectrometry (HPLC/MS) analyses of the liquid cultured KMC004 revealed six major constituents with characteristic quinone-like ultraviolet (UV) chromophores.9 To identify their molecular struc- tures, the whole culture broth (8 L) was extracted with ethyl ace- tate (16 L), and the extracts (1.2 g) were subjected to gradient reverse-phase chromatography. The six major metabolites were identiﬁed as known angucyclinone structures [MM 47755 (3),10 (+)-rubiginone B2 (4),11 (+)-ochromycinone (5),12 (+)-hatomarubi- gin A (6),13 (+)-rubiginone D2 (7),14 and X-14881 E (8)15 by comparing their spectroscopic data with previously reported spec- troscopic data (Fig. 1). Angucyclinones are characterized with an angular tetracyclic (benz[a]anthracene) carbon skeleton and are one of the many aromatic polyketides predominantly isolated from (cid:2) 2013 The Authors. soil-derived Streptomyces spp.16 Most of the previously reported angucyclinone analogues have exhibited a broad range of biologi- cal properties, including cytotoxicity,17 antibacterial,18 and platelet aggregation inhibition properties.19 To date, angucyclic quinones are continuously growing more attractive as a class of natural products due to their structural diversity, biomedical potential, and well-deﬁned biosynthetic pathways.16,20 Therefore, we inves- tigated the liquid culture media of KMC004 further to discover novel angucyclic quinones. Consequently, two highly oxygenated angucyclic quinones (Fig. 1) were isolated as minor constituents (1: 8 mg and 2: 5 mg) from ethyl acetate extracts (1.2 g) of Strepto- myces sp. KMC004 strain and named angumycinones A (1) and B (2). Herein, we describe the isolation, structure elucidation, and antimicrobial activities of 1 and 2.

Angumycinone A (1)21 was obtained as colorless block crystal with an assigned molecular formula of C19H16O6 based on our high resolution spectrometry (HRFABMS) data (obsd [M+H]+ m/z 341.1025, calcd 341.1025). The infrared (IR) spectrum of 1 displayed intense absorption bands at 3427 and 1640 cm(cid:2)1, suggesting the presence of hydroxyl and carbonyl groups, respectively. The UV spectrum of 1 revealed a qui- none-like chromophore.9 The 1H NMR spectrum was recorded in pyridine-d5 and displayed signals for three aromatic methines (dH 7.54, 7.43, and 7.21), a vinyl methine (dH 5.95), a methine (dH 4.56), three methylene groups [(dH 3.03, 2.49), (dH 3.00, 2.46), and (dH 1.84, 1.58)], a methyl (dH 1.76), and two exchangeable protons (dH 11.63 and 7.03). The 13C NMR spectrum revealed 19 including three aromatic methine carbons (dC 136.8, signals, 123.5, and 119.6), one vinyl methine carbon (dC 125.5), three aro- matic quaternary carbons (dC 161.1, 133.6, and 115.4), a vinyl qua- ternary carbon (dC 159.6), three carbonyl carbons (dC 197.9, 194.8, and 192.2), three oxygenated quaternary carbons (dC 68.7, 66.1, and 64.4), three methylene carbons (dC 46.2, 27.2, and 18.1), one methine carbon (dC 49.9), and a methyl carbon (dC 24.0). Analyses of the 1H and 13C NMR spectral data indicated that the compounds had characteristics of the tetracyclic benz[a]anthracene class, referring to an angular

carbon (dC 49.9), and a methyl carbon (dC 24.0). Analyses of the 1H and 13C NMR spectral data indicated that the compounds had characteristics of the tetracyclic benz[a]anthracene class, referring to an angularly constructed framework composed of four conjugated ring systems (rings A–D) (Table 1).16 Analyses of the extensive 2D NMR spectral data led to the identiﬁcation of the pla- nar structure of compound 1 (Fig. 2). The COSY correlations from both H-11 at dH 7.54 and H-9 at dH 7.21 (dd, J = 8.5, 1.5 Hz) to H-10 (dH 7.43, dd, J = 8.5, 7.5 Hz) suggested the presence of 1,2,3-trisubstituted benzene ring (D-ring). The aromatic methine H-10 (dH 7.43) exhibited a HMBC correlation to the oxygenated aromatic quaternary carbon C-8 (dC 161.1), and the phenolic OH signal attached at C-8 displayed a downﬁeld shifted proton reso- nance (dH 11.63) due to intramolecular hydrogen-bonding with the adjacent carbonyl C-7 (dC 197.9).22 An additional COSY correla- tion between two methylene groups [H2-5 (dH 1.84 and 1.58) and

Park et al. / Tetrahedron Letters 55 (2014) 63–66 H2-6 (dH 3.00 and 2.46)], coupled with HMBC correlations from methylene H2-6 to C-4a (dC 68.7), C-6a (dC 66.1), and C-12a (dC 64.4), and from another methylene H2-5 to C-4a (dC 68.7) and C-6a (dC 66.1), allowed us to construct the B-ring and assign its substituted pattern (Fig. 1). In addition, the construction of the A-ring was established with the HMBC correlations from the vinyl methine H-2 (dH 5.95) to C-4 (dC 46.2) and from a methyl singlet (dH 1.76) to C-2 (dC 125.5) and C-3 (dC 159.6), indicating the pres- ence of a methyl-substituted double bond.23 The connectivity of the A- and B-rings was achieved based on the HMBC correlations from H-2, H-4, and H2-5 to C-12b (dC 49.9) and from H-4 to C-5 (dC 27.2). Finally, the planar structure of 1 was determined using the HMBC correlations from H-11 and H-12b to C-12 (dC 192.2), in addition to the weak HMBC correlation between H-11 and C-7 (dC 197.9), suggesting that the C-ring was quinone-like. The exis- tence of an epoxide between C-6a (dC 66.1) and C-12a (dC 64.4) was deduced by comparing the 13C chemical shifts with the spectra data of previously reported compounds.24

The relative conﬁguration of H-12b was initially determined by interpreting the 2D NOESY NMR spectral data and long range cor- relation between H-12b and H-5b in the 1H–1H COSY spectrum of 1. The strong NOE correlation between the methine H-12b and H-4b indicated that these two protons were axially placed on the same side. The methane H-12b demonstrated a 1H–1H COSY corre- lation with H-5b, indicating the W-shape arrangement of the connecting bonds between H-12b and H-5b. This alignment was also supported by long range coupling (4J12b,5b = 2.0 Hz) between H-12b and H-5b proton signals in the 1H NMR spectrum of 1.25 These data allowed us to assign the relative conﬁguration of H-12b and H-5b to be cis-conﬁguration. The absolute conﬁguration of 1 was deduced with a direct method to be 4aR, 6aS, 12aR, and 12bR via single crystal X-ray diffraction analyses conducted with Mo Ka radiation, resulting in a reﬁned Flack parameter value of 1.2(9) using 1553 Friedel pairs (Fig. 3).26

Angumycinone B (2)27 was obtained as pale yellowish oil. An HRFABMS analysis indicated that the molecular formula of 2 was C19H16O7 (obsd [M+H]+ m/z 357. 0980, calcd 357.0974). The 1H and 13C NMR spectral data of 2 were very similar to that of 1; the major differences between the two data sets were signals indi- cating the presence of the additional hydroxyl group (dH 8.10) and an oxygenated methine (dH 5.23, dC 62.7),28 suggesting that 2 was a 6-hydroxy analogue of 1. The attachment of the hydroxyl group at C-6 in 2 was conﬁrmed by the COSY correlations of both H2-5 (dH 2.08 and 1.93) and 6-OH (dH 8.10) with H-6 (dH 5.23) and the HMBC correlation from H2-5 to C-6 (dC 62.7). The relative and absolute conﬁgurations of 2 were assigned by analyzing the NOESY correla- tions together with CD spectral data. The CD and NOESY spectra of 2 were very similar to that of 1. The broad singlet signal of H-6 in the 1H NMR spectrum of 2 and the key NOESY correlations of both axial H-5a and equatorial H-5b with H-6 suggested that the 6-OH was placed axially in the b-orientation, while H-6 was in an a- equatorial conﬁguration. In addition, the methane H-12b demon- strated a long range correlation (4J12b,5b = 2.3 Hz) with H-5b in the 1H–1H COSY and 1H NMR spectra of 2, indicating W-shape connection and cis-conﬁguration of H-12b and H-5b. The absolute conﬁguration of 2 was determined to be 4aS, 6R, 6aS, 12aR, and 12bR

, indicating W-shape connection and cis-conﬁguration of H-12b and H-5b. The absolute conﬁguration of 2 was determined to be 4aS, 6R, 6aS, 12aR, and 12bR and was validated with the very similar CD spectra of 2 and 1 (Fig. 4).

The angumycinones (1 and 2) represent highly oxygenated angucyclic quinones; this scaffold is characterized by the presence of an epoxide group situated between C-6a and C-12a. Only nine natural 6a,12a-epoxybenz[a]anthracene derivatives have been re- ported so far from soil-based Streptomyces species.9,14,23,24,28,29 Of these nine structures, angumycinone A (1) is the most similar in structure to grecocycline A aglycon, which features a hydroxyl group positioned at C-12b. Therefore, this Letter is the ﬁrst report establishing the absolute conﬁgurations of angucy- clic quinone structures via single-crystal X-ray diffraction analyses. Compounds 1–8 were tested for their antimicrobial activity against four Gram-positive bacteria, including Micrococcus luteus KCCM1548, Enterococcus hirae KCCM11768, Bacillus subtilis KCTC1021, and Staphylococcus aureus CCARM3089 (MRSA), in addi- tion to three Gram-negative bacteria (Salmonella typhimurium KCCM11862, Klebsiella pneumonia KCCM35454, and Escherichia coli KCTC2593) and three fungal strains (Aspergillus fumigatus HIC6094, Trichophyton albicans KCCM11282) using previously described minimum inhibitory con- centration (MIC) assay method.30 Ampicillin and amphotericin B were used as positive controls for pathogenic bacteria and fungi, respectively. Ampicillin exhibited antimicrobial activities against M. luteus, E. hirae, B. subtilis, MRSA, S. typhimurium, K. pneumonia, and E. coli with MIC values of 0.78, 0.78, 3.13, 12.5, 12.5, 12.5, and 6.25 lg/mL, respectively. Angumycinone A (1) exhibited moderate antimi- luteus and E. hirae (MIC values of crobial activities against M. 6.25 and 12.5 lg/mL, respectively); however, angumycinone B (2) was more active than 1 against the same strains (0.78 and 1.56 lg/mL, respectively). In addition, 2 demonstrated moderate activity against methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA), displaying a MIC value of 12.5 lg/mL. The three known angucyclinone ana- logues, 3, 5, and 8, also exhibited antimicrobial activity against M. luteus and E. hirae, while the other compounds (4, 6, and 7) were not active against any of the tested strains. MIC values of both compounds 3 and 5 were 0.39 and 0.78 lg/mL against M. luteus and E. hirae, respectively, while 8 displayed 0.39 lg/mL MIC value against both pathogenic bacteria. None of the compounds demon- strated any antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacterial or fungal strains. Technology institutional program, Grant numbers 2Z03840.
